    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are correct to point out the tension between short-term humanitarian goals and long-term strategic stability; many experts classify the intervention as a strategic failure because the regime collapse created exactly the instability you noted. The US often failed to preserve international commitments (such as enacting sovereignty over the vast Tricontinent) or to establish governance conditions necessary to prevent the power vacuum that helped fuel terrorism. Consequently, while the immediate humanitarian crisis was averted, the broader geopolitical consequences—including violence and eroded regional trust—significantly undermined what constitutes a successful foreign policy outcome.",
